  "sources": [
    {
      "title": "Sharks Don't Get Cancer - Wikipedia",
      "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharks_Don't_Get_Cancer",
      "content": "Robert S. Langer, a co-author of the 1983 study showing that shark cartilage inhibited the growth of blood vessels toward tumors, along with Judah Folkman, a professor of surgery at Harvard Medical School, said in an interview that Lane was &quot;inappropriately using our published work and our names to imply that we support his claims.&quot; A 2004 paper in Cancer Research said that even if sharks did rarely get cancer, as Lane claims, &quot;cancer incidence is irrelevant to the use of crude extracts for cancer treatment.&quot;"
    },
    {
      "title": "Blowing Shark Cartilage out of the Water | Science | AAAS",
      "url": "https://www.science.org/content/article/blowing-shark-cartilage-out-water",
      "content": "Sharks do have a <strong>low cancer incidence</strong>, researchers say."
    },
    {
      "title": "Long-term Observation of Cancer in a Shark — Shark Research Institute",
      "url": "https://www.sharks.org/blog/blogs/science-blog/long-term-observation-cancer-shark",
      "content": "Sick individuals are easily predated by other animals, and since dead sharks sink to the ocean floor, rather than float or beach as do marine mammals, shark cancer deaths are rarely detected. Despite there being substantial evidence in the scientific literature of sharks with cancer, I am always interested in new documentation of these cases."
    },
    {
      "title": "Shark cartilage, cancer and the growing threat of pseudoscience",
      "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15574750/",
      "content": "Checking your browser before accessing pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov · Click here if you are not automatically redirected after 5 seconds"
    },
    {
      "title": "The Mysteries of Cancer in Sharks: Insights and Implications",
      "url": "https://apexpredators.com/cancer-in-sharks/",
      "content": "We now know that sharks do get cancer and they do get sick. <strong>There have been tumours found in over 23 different shark species across the world</strong>. One of the main reasons as to why sharks are getting cancer is pollution."
    }
  ],
